### Critical

#### C01: Exception swallowed in grammeter offline path

##### Where

`src/tremie/fault.py:61`


##### Issue

The `except Exception` block at line 61 logs the error and returns `None` without re-raising
or surfacing a fault code. Callers cannot distinguish a grammeter offline event from a
successful no-op.


##### Impact

Any code path that depends on a fault code to halt lotus-o-delta routing will silently
continue when the grammeter is offline, producing undefined waneshaft behavior.


##### Fix

Replace the bare `return None` with `raise TremieFaultError(FaultCode.GRAMMETER_OFFLINE)`.
Add a test asserting the fault code is raised when the grammeter mock is offline.


##### Outcome


----

### Significant

#### S01: Mid-routing fault test missing fault code assertion

##### Where

`tests/test_tremie.py:104`


##### Issue

`test_mid_route_girdlespring_fault` asserts that `route()` raises an exception but does not
assert which fault code is raised. Any exception — including an unexpected `RuntimeError` —
would pass the test.


##### Fix

Replace `pytest.raises(Exception)` with `pytest.raises(TremieFaultError)` and add
`assert exc.code == FaultCode.GIRDLESPRING_FAULT` in the `with` block.


##### Outcome


----

